## Introduction and overview

Our product will be a gambling simulation with multiple casino games for users to try their luck on. Our purpose for the game is to give people the rush and excitement of gambling without the risk of actually losing money. This can either help people who have a gambling addiction overcome said addiction or help make the new generation of casino goers. Some of its core features will include an open 3D environment to simulate how a real casino feels, with the sounds and bright flashing lights to make it feel like you are really there. As well as a few classic casino games, like slot machines, blackjack and craps. This will be targeted to an audience of people above the legal age to gamble. This will be on a desktop platform with a downloaded application.  The game will not arrive with real money transfers at the start, so you can't make real money from it.

	public void Shuffle(){

        		secondCard = tempCard;  //swaps second card with first

## Proof Of Concept for Craps

### Core Technical Difficulties

	The expected difficulties moving forward with the craps game are the UI design and game logic. In order to make the game fun and easy to play, the UI must be simple and clear. At no time should the player be confused what bets have been made, or the current state of the round. Since there are many different types of bets in craps, it will be difficult and time consuming to implement all the logic behind each bet. There may be difficulties with certain outcomes, so sufficient testing will need to be done to ensure the game works properly.

## Proof Of Concept for Slots

### Core Technical Difficulties

In this section, we outline the main technical challenges encountered during the development of the slot machine feature:

1) Random Number Generation: Implementing a fair and random method for generating slot numbers (will be replaced with icons/symbols in the future) each time the user spins.  
2) User Interface Interaction: Creating an interactive button that triggers the spin action, displaying the results properly, and showing dynamically the changed balance.  
3) Game Logic for Scoring: Developing the logic to calculate wins based on the combination of displayed numbers.  
4) Animation and Visual Effects: Implementing smooth animations for the slot machine reels during the spin and providing visual feedback on outcomes.

### Needs for to Demonstrate

In this section, we outline the individual approaches taken to demonstrate a working solution for each component of the proof of concept.

1) Random Number Generator (in Unity)  
   The objective here is to implement a function that utilizes a random number generator to select values that represent icons/symbols (e.g., cherries, oranges, blueberries, watermelons, bells, bars, crowns, and 7s). This approach ensures varied outcomes for each spin.  
2) Spin Button (in Unity)  
   The objective here is to create a UI button using Unity's UI system that allows users to initiate the spin action. This button will trigger the random number generation and facilitate user interaction with the game.  
3) Score Calculation Logic (in Unity)  
   The objective here is to develop a method that evaluates the resulting numbers after a spin. This method will update the player's score based on the combination of numbers displayed, ensuring accurate scoring and feedback for the player.

### Code

    public TextMeshProUGUI reel1, reel2, reel3;  // References for each reel text  
    public int payoutMultiplier \= 10; // Adjust payout

    private int\[\] results \= new int\[3\];

    public void Spin()  
    {  
        // Generate a random number for each reel  
        results\[0\] \= Random.Range(1, 8); // 1 to 7  
        results\[1\] \= Random.Range(1, 8);  
        results\[2\] \= Random.Range(1, 8);

        // Display each number on the respective reel  
        reel1.text \= results\[0\].ToString();  
        reel2.text \= results\[1\].ToString();  
        reel3.text \= results\[2\].ToString();

        CalculatePayout();  // Calculate the payout based on the results  
    }

    // Calculates payout based on matches  
    private void CalculatePayout()  
    {  
        if (results\[0\] \== results\[1\] && results\[1\] \== results\[2\]) // All three match  
        {  
            int payout \= results\[0\] \* payoutMultiplier;  
            Debug.Log("Jackpot\! Payout: " \+ payout);  
        }  
        else if (results\[0\] \== results\[1\] || results\[1\] \== results\[2\] || results\[0\] \== results\[2\]) // Two match  
        {  
            int payout \= 5;  
            Debug.Log("Partial Match\! Payout: " \+ payout);  
        }  
        else  
        {  
            Debug.Log("No match, better luck next time\!");  
        }  
    }  
}

### Results

The proof of concept has successfully demonstrated the following:

1) Random Number Generation: The slot machine displays different numbers each time the spin button is pressed.  
2) User Interface Interaction: The spin button triggers the spinning action and updates the displayed numbers as expected.  
3) Score Calculation Logic: The basic scoring system can determine winning conditions based on matched numbers, which can be enhanced further for more complex gameplay.

The current RNG and scoring logic is basic and will need refinement to handle various payout structures and more complex winning combinations. We will enhance the UI for a better user experience. Also we will add sound effects and improve animations to create a more engaging gameplay experience.  
Instead of using a function to randomly select symbols from a predefined set of items like cherries, oranges, blueberries, watermelons, bells, bars, crowns, and 7s, we implemented a random number generator. If we decide to move forward with the RNG, the random number generator will produce a number that corresponds to an index in an array of symbols in. Each number generated will be mapped to a specific symbol, allowing for a simple and effective way to select random symbols for the slot machine. This approach streamlines the selection process while ensuring that the symbols are chosen randomly from the predefined set.
